    "created_at": "2015-06-11T22:50:41Z",
    "updated_at": "2015-06-11T22:50:41Z",
    "body": "You don't need a native API to do this. You can detect the OS to do the appropriate work around by passing a shell command. All of which is supported by node out of the box.\n\nSuch as XDG for linux: `xdg-screensaver suspend [window id]`\n\nLook for stderr output to see if it didn't take and do dbux instead:\n\n```\ndbus-send --session \\\n      --dest=org.gnome.ScreenSaver \\\n      --type=method_call \\\n      --print-reply \\\n      --reply-timeout=20000 \\\n      /org/gnome/ScreenSaver \\\n      org.gnome.ScreenSaver.Inhibit \\\n      [application name e.g. \"\"] \\\n      [reason e.g.\"playing a game\"] \\\n      [non-zero-random-integer e.g. 123]\n```\n\nOn Windows you can disable it on video start: `reg add “HKEY_CURRENT_USERControl PanelDesktop” /v ScreenSaveActive /t REG_SZ /d 0 /f`\n\nAnd then disable it on video end: `reg add “HKEY_CURRENT_USERControl PanelDesktop” /v ScreenSaveActive /t REG_SZ /d 1 /f`\n\nI am sure there are classier ways for the ones listed and even more ways for other platforms that might be out there. I found these with a quick Google search. A little bit of research/code you could rig all this into a node package with ease. Most native applications that need to inhibit screensavers do similar methods. So I don't see how doing it from a node module would not be a good approach.\n"
  },
