    "created_at": "2015-06-12T05:34:44Z",
    "updated_at": "2015-06-12T07:22:34Z",
    "body": "> As far as I can see, this isn't true - the only place I see where you can inhibit the screensaver is in the  Pepper Flash host, and it's a one-off Windows only thing. The cross-platform support for screensavers in Chromium seems to only be to query whether it's running or not.\n\nWhat about the `<video>` tag? It inhibits the screensaver perfectly on every OS.\n\n@baconface this seems like a stable solution for Linux. As for Windows, what will happen if the app quits unexpectedly? Will the screensaver stay disabled forever?\n\nOn OS X, the two options are `pmset noidle` and modifying the plist. I don't know the side effects that both have.\n\nThis is doable, but as I said, platform specific and those solutions might have side effects. That's why I'd prefer a stable (as possible) solution, but if there's no easy way to expose this I guess a node.js module would be best.\n"
  },
